My friend and I came here by chance walking down the street, it's was a very awkward experience as we were not dressed for the occasion however the staff and other guests kept staring at us, when we first walked in one of   the waiters looked us up and down as we were standing waiting to be seated, he then said he had to check on something (he kind of muttered so I believe that's what he said) and went to the kitchen, came back about 3 minutes later with (I believe) was the owner of the restaurant and he sat us. I overheard conversations about us but I do respect the owner as I overheard him say you must respect them to his employee. Food was generally good, I ordered the Homemade Lasagna and I wasn't very impressed but still did not taste bad, just in my opinion not worth the $25 plus a tip on top of that. Also the waiter we had did not ask us for anything to drink besides filling up our water glasses and rushed the entire process, immediately asked if we were ready to order our food. Later on during the beginning of our meal a couple came in, was sat in front of the window to the left of us and the same waiter approached their table and begun first with "Hello how are you this evening" the couple responds, he then asks "may I start you with something to drink" ... Totally different attitude! It was like night and day. They were never intentionally judging us or using slander, but the underlying tone and affect was there. Disappointed but perhaps if I came prepare and dressed the part (and wasn't wearing a god damn baseball cap and backpack) the service would of been better, perhaps the food as well.

Italian food is usually good. Neighborhood pizza places do well with dishes beyond hero sandwiches and calzone and can offer a delicious picatta or carbonara. Queen takes its place in a different tier, one that's upscale. Our party of seven traveled there to celebrate an occasion and everyone was pleased. There is an inclusive wine list offering Bolla to Dom Perignon. Bread includes crusty, sticks, and focaccia with herb flavored evoo. Appetizers we tried were delicious stuffed oysters, well prepared stuffed artichokes, broccoli rabe with homemade sausage, and caprice with homemade mozzarella. Every selection was special. Oops, a bit of grizzle in the sausage. I chose saltimbocca, perfectly prepared in sage favored gravy with a potato coquette. My wife had sea scallops browned and delicate, every bite perfect. Dessert was great. Espresso was well done. Service was carefull and attentive, I always had a full water glass, all the dishes arrived simultaneously, delivered to the right person individually.

You've GOT to be kidding me. Zagat rated probably because they polish up their act when it comes time for evaluation. The food itself is good enough. Just to check it wasn't the typical bad service when you're at a 'table for one' or 'dining while black' I asked a British guy sitting behind me who had his kids with him. He confirmed that the service was a hot mess but affirmed that the food is good. The little old guy (greeter I think) was pleasant and brought me a menu within 5 minutes. Then some other dude poured water and brought bread within 2 minutes. But it was all downhill after that. Subpar service whilst being expensive with adequate but not mind-blowing cuisine. Oh yes, I called after leaving so I could connect with the manager -was told he is 'busy' and would call me back. Guess who is still (not) waiting for that call.

I actually am not a big fan of pancakes, so I ordered the smoked salmon scramble. It was so delicious! The eggs were on the softer side, and they had a generous amount of house-made lox mixed in. I put a little of their homemade hot sauce on the eggs which was great. My dish came with toast on the side. Generally, toast is pretty boring, but I put their homemade raspberry jam on it, and it became the most amazing toast I had every tasted! I lathered on that jam so that it was more jam than toast. I will come back just for the jam. It also came with a mixed green salad which was topped with a tasty vinaigrette. I appreciated the healthy addition to the dish.  My friends were equally satisfied with their meals. My friend visiting from out of town obviously got the pancakes. She had the chocolate chunk version. The portion was very large, and they were delicious (I did have a taste). They were fluffy, very and some of the best pancakes I've had. My other friend had the omelette. The portion was also large, and she was a big fan.  This is a great spot to take visitors for the famous pancakes, but I will definitely come back just for a regular brunch. I might just try to come at an off time to try to avoid the ridiculous waits.

Consistent food of the highest quality. Always coupled with professional service!  A favorite lunch place for local bankers to take their best clients and prospects to lunch.  Private conversations over the best Italian cuisine always lead to happy clients.
It's a little pricey, and the service, though friendly and professional, can be a little haphazard. But this place has many ways to win you over, starting with the food.
Good food & service
Classic Italian eatery that's been here forever. Great food, no complaints.

Wonderful food served by a highly professional wait staff -- the kind that are hard to find these days--that does not interrupt constantly with a mechanical "how is everything?" They just anticipate what you may need, be it bread, more water, Parmesan cheese, whatever, and it just arrives. The seating can be a little tight particularly at lunch but the noise level is good and the menu features some of the best classic Italian food in Brooklyn;  well worth the price.

Excellent food and very welcoming. I consider myself a connoisseur of fine italian food and this is near the top of my list. I had the Pasta Nero which had two of the largest scallops that I have ever seen. My companion had the gnocchi, which was light and fluffy and very flavorful.
WONDERFUL HUMBLE OWNER NAMED PAT. LOVELY PLACE... CLEAN WHITE TABLE CLOTH. BEST ITALIAN WITH IN WALKING DISTANCE FROM THE BROOKLYN MARRIOTT

Great food. BUT, this isn't the place to come when you are very hungry, or in a rush. They take their time, and i just love it. And more important, it really worth the waiting. So take the time and enjoy delicious Italian food.
(Translated by Google) Excellent  (Original) Excelente
I really liked the smiling, friendly, old-school atmosphere. Busy, but everyone was relaxed and seemed happy. I really liked the alle gamberi, which was shrimp sauce and linguine. Delicious!
Delicious old-school white-tablecloth Italian. Expect to invest a serious amount of time for a meal here - they take their time to a fault.
Classic New York Italian place.
A very classic Brooklyn Italian restaurant. Feels a little bit dated inside, but that's what adds to the vibe. The food is delicious from the bread, to their salads, pastas and entrees.
Wonderful authentic Italian food.  Just wonderful quaint place!  Awesome bread basket right down to the dessert and Italian coffee!
Good fare and I know b/c I am Italian ;-)
A great dining experience!

Old World favorites with a  modern flair. This Brooklyn Heights restaurant is a hidden gem, with the best mozzarella in the city, fresh homemade pasta. You will never leave this place hungry. If it was in Manhattan, would be impossible to get a reservation.
A good classic italian in Brooklyn. The best olive oil in downtown BK

Queen Italian restaurant is a local favorite. They do everything right. Plus it is unpretentious. This is a place where people go to celebrate. There were lots of birthday parties when we went. I don’t blame them. The food is good and everything is so casual in the midst of white table cloths! The bread basket has a variety from focaccia to crackers to breadsticks. For dinner I mixed and matched a few things. One of the best things I tried were the figs wrapped in prosciutto drizzled in honey on top of ricotta cheese. The gnocchi tricolore deserved high honors as well. For dessert we shared the warm chocolate tort with vanilla gelato and raspberry sauce. The cannoli either comes giant or as three mini ones on the plate. Don’t forget to share!
The fry bread to start with is a little bit of heaven. I have a very good scallop and shrimp pasta. Service was attentive and very polite.

One of the oldest Italians restaurants in Brooklyn. They have a brunch on Saturday and Sunday. Good food and drink. Disappointed in the fact, we asked for the special and was told they were not offering it at this time. But saw the special was advertised in window.

Classic, family run Brooklyn red sauce Italian joint. Probably one of the nicest restaurants in this gritty, commercial strip of downtown Brooklyn (even if it may not look it from the outside). Got here late on a Saturday w/large party and no reservation and they could not have been nicer or more accommodating! Formal and attentive waitstaff. Tasty and well portioned dishes. Their mozzarella is made fresh on site daily, I'm told. Trivia: this was a favorite haunt of Jules Feiffer's and Norton Juster's when they were roommates in Brooklyn Heights and working on the Phantom Tollbooth!
Had a wonderful meal at a place I haven't been to in a long time. Fresh Mozzarella was wonderful. Service as remembered was very good
Attentive service meets cooking that is always good and sometimes really good.
the food is always good here.  a neighborhood staple.  the servers are very knowledgable however our last visit they were very slow to take our order.

this long time local favorite still delivers great tasting italian food and good value. disregard the neon sign outside; this is no diner type but a well run, handsome place inside. osso buco and lasagna dishes are superb. vegetables are crisp and delicious.
